---js
const layout = "layouts/home.njk";
const title = "AI for Engineering Teams — Berlin";
const description = "Matt Richards — AI adoption for engineering teams, from Berlin. Workflow design, guardrails, and team health for engineering orgs using AI every day without rotting the codebase or the craft.";
const sitemap = { priority: "0.9", changefreq: "monthly" };
---
{% css %}
@layer page {
	{% include "css/landing.css" %}
	{% include "css/services-grid.css" %}
}
{% endcss %}

<article class="landing">
	<nav class="landing-crumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
		<a href="/">Home</a>
		<span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
		<a href="/freelance-tech-lead-berlin/">Freelance</a>
		<span class="sep" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
		<span aria-current="page">AI for engineering teams</span>
	</nav>

	<header class="landing-hero">
		<p class="landing-eyebrow">Matt Richards &middot; Berlin</p>
		<h1><em>AI</em> for engineering teams.</h1>
		<p class="lede">Keeping humans, products and codebases healthy in the age of AI is the engineering problem of the decade. I help engineering leaders use AI every day &mdash; without rotting the codebase or the craft.</p>
		<div class="landing-meta">
			<a class="eyebrow-link" href="/contact">Start a conversation</a>
			<span class="landing-locator"><span class="online-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>Currently open to new work</span>
		</div>
	</header>

	<section class="landing-services" aria-label="What I help engineering teams with">
		<div class="service">
			<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 01</span>
			<h2 class="service-head">Workflow design</h2>
			<p class="service-body">Where AI helps. Where it hurts. Where it quietly lies. Setting up the rails your team can actually live with, not the demo-ware your vendor is selling.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="service">
			<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 02</span>
			<h2 class="service-head">Guardrails</h2>
			<p class="service-body">Review discipline, test coverage, refactor hygiene. Stopping autocomplete from silently compounding debt. Shipping at speed without shipping rot.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="service">
			<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 03</span>
			<h2 class="service-head">Team health</h2>
			<p class="service-body">Junior engineers still need to grow up. Seniors still need time to think. AI changes both shapes &mdash; and I've thought about this one a lot.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="landing-section">
		<h2><span class="ix">&sect; 04 &mdash; What I help with</span>The engagements that fit</h2>
		<div class="landing-body">
			<p>I use AI every day, read the research, and watch closely what it's doing to the craft &mdash; to team shape, to code quality, to how junior engineers grow up in a world where the easy work is suddenly cheap. Most of what engineering leaders need now isn't another tool demo; it's a clear-eyed take on what's actually changing.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Tool evaluation</strong> &mdash; Claude Code, Copilot, Cursor, and the rest. An honest read on what fits your team, your code and your risk appetite.</li>
				<li><strong>Team playbooks</strong> &mdash; how your team actually uses AI. Prompts, workflows, review norms, the little rules that keep quality up.</li>
				<li><strong>Hiring &amp; levelling</strong> &mdash; what to hire for now. How to read a senior when the easy signals are cheaper than ever. How juniors grow up in the new shape.</li>
				<li><strong>Code review practices</strong> &mdash; the human work that matters more, not less. Stopping autocomplete from slipping past the gate.</li>
				<li><strong>Metric design</strong> &mdash; what to measure, what to ignore. Velocity is mostly a lie; a few things are worth tracking.</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="landing-section">
		<h2><span class="ix">&sect; 05 &mdash; Where I'm coming from</span>Twenty years of craft, in the new weather</h2>
		<div class="landing-body">
			<p>I'm a senior+ product engineer and engineering lead with twenty years in. Platform-first. SOLID by default. Allergic to framework-of-the-month thinking. Which is exactly why the AI conversation matters to me: the fundamentals that used to take years to pick up are the things most at risk of being quietly skipped.</p>
			<p>Keeping humans, products and codebases healthy in the age of AI is the engineering problem of the decade. I help teams avoid both failure modes: getting left behind, and letting an autocomplete quietly rot the codebase.</p>
			<p>I write about this &mdash; craft, leadership, and keeping codebases humane in the age of autocomplete. <a href="/words">The words archive &rarr;</a></p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="services-section" aria-labelledby="related-services-heading">
		<h2 id="related-services-heading">Related services</h2>
		<ul class="services-grid">
			<li class="service">
				<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 01</span>
				<h3 class="service-head">Fractional engineering lead</h3>
				<p class="service-body">Senior engineering leadership, part-time. Strategy, team shape, architecture, mentorship.</p>
				<a class="cta" href="/fractional-engineering-lead-berlin/">Fractional engineering lead</a>
			</li>
			<li class="service">
				<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 02</span>
				<h3 class="service-head">Architecture review</h3>
				<p class="service-body">Honest read on what's load-bearing, what's rot, what's worth the rewrite. Scoped, two weeks.</p>
				<a class="cta" href="/software-architecture-review-berlin/">Software architecture review</a>
			</li>
			<li class="service">
				<span class="service-kicker">&sect; 03</span>
				<h3 class="service-head">Freelance tech lead</h3>
				<p class="service-body">Hands-on technical leadership. Twenty years in. Berlin, EU, remote.</p>
				<a class="cta" href="/freelance-tech-lead-berlin/">Freelance tech lead, Berlin</a>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="landing-next" aria-label="Where to go next">
		<div class="next">
			<span class="next-kicker">Background</span>
			<h3>About</h3>
			<p>Twenty years, two sides of the bench: product engineering and engineering leadership.</p>
			<a class="cta" href="/about">Read the long version</a>
		</div>
		<div class="next">
			<span class="next-kicker">Writing</span>
			<h3>Words</h3>
			<p>Notes on craft, leadership, and the age of AI. The archive &mdash; dated, unvarnished.</p>
			<a class="cta" href="/words">Open the archive</a>
		</div>
		<div class="next">
			<span class="next-kicker">Work together</span>
			<h3>Contact</h3>
			<p>Email, Signal, or the form. Tell me what you're building and what's in the way.</p>
			<a class="cta" href="/contact">Get in touch</a>
		</div>
	</section>
</article>

